    "format-version": "0.1",
    "name": "MRSA mobile-AMR + structural annotation (Bakta/JBrowse)",
    "report": {
        "markdown": "# MRSA mobile-AMR context with structural annotation\n\nFour complete *Staphylococcus aureus* isolates from Hikichi et al. 2019 (BioProject `PRJDB8599`) were imported as combined chromosome + plasmid FASTA into **one collection** and scanned \u2014 **all steps mapped over that collection** \u2014 with **staramr** (ResFinder + PlasmidFinder + MLST), **ISEScan** + **Integron Finder** for mobile elements, **bedtools closest** for ARG\u2194IS distances, and now **Bakta** whole-genome annotation for the flanking-gene context plus per-isolate **JBrowse** genome browsers. The comparative question: **which resistance genes sit in mobile genomic contexts, how does that context differ between related isolates, and what genes flank each mobile-AMR locus?**\n\nBecause every step is a collection map-over and every displayed figure is a real tool output, this whole notebook **extracts to a single reusable workflow**.\n\n## Isolates\n\n| Strain | MLST | Chromosome | Plasmid | Genome (bp) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| KUH140013 | ST8 | AP020311 | AP020312 | 2,837,394 |\n| KUH140046 | ST8 | AP020313 | AP020314 | 2,859,431 |\n| KUH180129 | ST6313 | AP020322 | AP020323 | 2,897,282 |\n| KUN1163 | ST764 | AP020324 | AP020325 | 2,944,787 |\n\nThree distinct sequence types (ST8 \u00d72, ST6313, ST764), so differences below are between *related but non-clonal* backgrounds. The two ST8 isolates are the natural clonal pair to contrast.\n\n## AMR gene presence / absence\n\nPresence/absence matrix, annotated with genomic location (**P** = plasmid, **C** = chromosome):\n\n| Gene | Class | KUH140013 | KUH140046 | KUH180129 | KUN1163 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| `mecA` | methicillin (SCC*mec*) | C | C | **\u2013** | C |\n| `blaZ` | \u03b2-lactam | C | C | **P** | \u2013 |\n| `aac(6')-aph(2'')` | aminoglycoside | \u2013 | **P** | C | **P** |\n| `ant(9)-Ia` | spectinomycin | \u2013 | C | C | C |\n| `erm(A)` | MLS_B | \u2013 | C | C | C |\n| `tet(M)` | tetracycline | \u2013 | \u2013 | C | C |\n| `fosD` | fosfomycin | \u2013 | **P** | \u2013 | \u2013 |\n| `aadD` | aminoglycoside | \u2013 | \u2013 | \u2013 | C |\n| `bleO` | bleomycin | \u2013 | \u2013 | \u2013 | C |\n\nThe same data as a heatmap (0 = absent, 1 = chromosome, 2 = plasmid) \u2014 built from the pipeline, not pasted. The teal (plasmid) cells carry the comparative story:\n\n```galaxy\nhistory_dataset_as_image(output=\"heatmap2 on dataset 121\")\n```\n\nTwo findings stand out:\n\n1. **KUH180129 carries no `mecA`** \u2014 genotypically MSSA, an outlier in a set otherwise defined by methicillin resistance. Its \u03b2-lactam resistance rests on `blaZ` alone, and that `blaZ` is plasmid-borne.\n2. **The resistome scales with, but is not explained by, lineage.** The two ST8 isolates are far apart: KUH140013 carries only `blaZ`+`mecA`, while its clonemate KUH140046 adds an aminoglycoside / MLS_B / fosfomycin load. Within one ST, almost the entire difference is mobile-element cargo.\n\n> staramr flags all four genomes as *quality-failed* only because the expected genome-size window (4\u20136 Mb) is set for larger organisms; *S. aureus* genomes are ~2.8\u20132.9 Mb. The ResFinder / PlasmidFinder calls are unaffected.\n\n## Mobile elements: insertion sequences and integrons\n\n**Integron Finder detected zero integrons in any isolate** \u2014 expected for *S. aureus*: resistance mobility here is insertion-sequence / transposon / plasmid-driven, not integron-driven.\n\n```galaxy\nhistory_dataset_as_table(output=\"Collapse Collection on dataset 77, 80, and others and collection 74\")\n```\n\n**ISEScan** (complete elements only, `remove_short_is=true`) finds insertion sequences everywhere \u2014 the IS6 family disproportionately on the plasmids (IS6/IS257 drives staphylococcal resistance-plasmid mosaicism), and an **IS256 expansion on KUH180129's chromosome** (the basis of Tn4001).\n\n### ARG \u2192 nearest insertion sequence (bedtools closest)\n\nEach isolate's ResFinder hits and ISEScan elements are converted to BED, sorted, and run through **bedtools `closest -d`**, **mapped over the collection** \u2014 so the distance computation is a reusable part of the history graph. The combined per-isolate result:\n\n```galaxy\nhistory_dataset_as_table(output=\"Collapse Collection on dataset 116-119 and collection 115\")\n```\n\n| Isolate | Gene | Location | Nearest IS | Distance |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| KUN1163 | `aac(6')-aph(2'')` | plasmid AP020325 | **IS6** | **80 bp** |\n| KUH140046 | `aac(6')-aph(2'')` | plasmid AP020314 | **IS6** | 467 bp |\n| KUH180129 | `aac(6')-aph(2'')` | **chromosome** AP020322 | **IS256** | **84 bp** |\n\n**This is the demo's headline.** The same gene, **`aac(6')-aph(2'')`, sits in a different mobile context depending on location** \u2014 adjacent to an **IS6** element on the plasmids of KUN1163 (80 bp) and KUH140046 (467 bp), but adjacent to an **IS256** element on the chromosome of KUH180129 (84 bp). Same resistance gene, different mobilizing-element family \u2014 the IS6/IS257 plasmid pool vs the IS256/Tn4001 chromosomal route.\n\nCounting every ARG by mobile context (plasmid / chromosomal IS-adjacent <1 kb / chromosomal distal) shows the comparative burden composition:\n\n```galaxy\nhistory_dataset_as_image(output=\"heatmap2 on dataset 122\")\n```\n\n## Structural gene context (Bakta)\n\n`bedtools closest` reports the nearest IS regardless of biological relationship. To confirm the mobile context **structurally**, every isolate's genome was annotated with **Bakta** (mapped over the collection), and each ResFinder hit was matched to its **nearest flanking annotated gene** (`bedtools closest -io` of the ARG BED against the Bakta CDS features, mapped). This recovers the genomic *neighbourhood* of each resistance locus:\n\n```galaxy\nhistory_dataset_as_table(output=\"Text reformatting on dataset 165\")\n```\n\nThe flanking genes confirm the composite-transposon / operon structure the proximity analysis implied:\n\n- **`blaZ` \u2192 `blaR1`** (65 bp): the \u03b2-lactamase regulator, the canonical *blaZ\u2013blaR1\u2013blaI* operon.\n- **`erm(A)` \u2194 `ant(9)-Ia`** (126 bp, reciprocal): the gene content of the **Tn554** transposon (MLS_B + spectinomycin), recurring at multiple chromosomal loci.\n- **`tet(M)` \u2192 IS256 family transposase** (KUH180129): tet(M) sitting in the IS256-dense chromosomal region.\n- **`aac(6')-aph(2'')` \u2192 aminoglycoside N-acetyltransferase neighbour** (1 bp): the bifunctional AAC(6')-APH(2'') locus, with **IS256-family transposase** flanking it on the KUH180129 chromosome (= **Tn4001**) \u2014 the structural confirmation of the headline.\n\n## Genome browsers (per isolate)\n\nEach isolate's assembly is rendered as an interactive **JBrowse** browser (mapped over the collection \u2192 one browser per isolate), with three tracks: **resistance genes** (ResFinder), **insertion sequences** (ISEScan), and the full **Bakta annotation**. Navigate any browser to a resistance locus to see the ARG, its flanking IS element, and the Bakta gene context together. The headline locus to inspect: on **KUH180129**, `aac(6')-aph(2'')` on the chromosome (`ENA|AP020322|AP020322.1` ~2,084 kb) with **IS256** 84 bp downstream and a Bakta-annotated *IS256 family transposase* alongside.\n\n**KUH140013** (ST8, minimal resistome):\n\n\n\n**KUH140046** (ST8, plasmid `aac(6')-aph(2'')`+`fosD`+IS6):\n\n\n\n**KUH180129** (MSSA, chromosomal `aac(6')-aph(2'')`+IS256 \u2014 the headline contrast):\n\n\n\n**KUN1163** (ST764, plasmid `aac(6')-aph(2'')`+IS6):\n\n\n\n## Pipeline (structured for workflow extraction)\n\nEvery tool step runs **mapped over the `MRSA isolate assemblies` collection**, so the whole analysis \u2014 spine, Bakta enrichment, and JBrowse \u2014 extracts as a single reusable, sample-agnostic workflow:\n\n```\nassemblies (collection)\n  \u251c\u2500 staramr \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500 resfinder.tsv \u2500 awk\u2192BED \u2500 SortBED \u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510\n  \u2502                                                  \u2502                         \u2502\n  \u251c\u2500 ISEScan \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500 results.gff \u2500\u2500\u2500 awk\u2192BED \u2500 SortBED \u2500\u2534 bedtools closest -d \u2500 Collapse \u2500 awk \u2192 matrices \u2192 heatmaps\n  \u2502               tabular \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500 awk\u2192BED \u2500 tbl2gff3 \u2192 IS GFF3 \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510\n  \u251c\u2500 Integron Finder \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500 (zero integrons)                          \u2502\n  \u2514\u2500 Bakta \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500 GFF3 \u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500 awk\u2192CDS BED \u2500 SortBED \u2500 closest -io (vs ARG) \u2192 flanking-gene table\n                         \u2502  resfinder BED \u2500 tbl2gff3 \u2192 ARG GFF3 \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2524\n                         \u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2534\u2500 JBrowse (ref + ARG/IS/Bakta tracks) \u2192 per-isolate browsers\n```\n\n## Method caveats\n\n- **Single-database, single-version calls.** ResFinder / PlasmidFinder / ISEScan / Integron Finder / Bakta results are database-version-dependent; treat as a snapshot.\n- **Adjacency vs mobilization.** `bedtools closest` distances are descriptive; the firm comparative call (`aac(6')-aph(2'')`'s IS6\u2194IS256 flip) rests on three isolates agreeing and is now corroborated structurally by the Bakta flanking-gene annotation (Tn4001 IS256 transposase).\n- **No SCC*mec* typing tool** was run; **PointFinder disabled**, so chromosomal point-mutation resistance was not assessed.\n",
        "title": "MRSA mobile-AMR + structural annotation (Bakta/JBrowse)"
    },
